05239nam a22009495i 9780271094106DE-B159720221205051307.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221205t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a9780271094106  a(DE-B1597)642533  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aN7989.6.C6bF76 2022eb 7aART0150102bisacsh04a255/.36096751/14012221 aFromont, Cécile, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImages on a Mission in Early Modern Kongo and Angola /cCécile Fromont. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 “Nonsense” Capuchin Images of Kongo and Angola Against Italian Preconceptions -- tChapter 2 Practical Guides to the Mission: The Capuchin Central- African Corpus -- tChapter 3 Images and Devotion -- tChapter 4 Images as Method -- tChapter 5 Images Against Idolatry -- tChapter 6 With “the Consent of the People, and the Secular Arm of the Prince” -- tChapter 7 Penned by Encounter: Capuchins, Central Africans, and the Making of a Cross-Cultural Discourse -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEarly modern central Africa comes to life in an extraordinary atlas of vivid watercolors and drawings that Italian Capuchin Franciscans, veterans of Kongo and Angola missions, composed between 1650 and 1750 for the training of future missionaries. These “practical guides” present the intricacies of the natural, social, and religious environment of seventeenth- and eighteenth-century west-central Africa and outline the primarily visual catechization methods the friars devised for the region. Images on a Mission in Early Modern Kongo and Angola brings this overlooked visual corpus to public and scholarly attention.This beautifully illustrated book includes full-color reproductions of all the images in the atlas, in conjunction with rarely seen related material gathered from collections and archives around the world. Taking a bold new approach to the study of early modern global interactions, art historian Cécile Fromont demonstrates how visual creations such as the Capuchin vignettes, though European in form and crafstmanship, emerged not from a single perspective but rather from cross-cultural interaction. Fromont models a fresh way to think about images created across cultures, highlighting the formative role that cultural encounter itself played in their conception, execution, and modes of operation.Centering Africa and Africans, and with ramifications on four continents, Fromont’s decolonial history profoundly transforms our understanding of the early modern world. It will be of substantial interest to specialists in early modern studies, art history, and religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aCapuchin artzAngolay17th century. 0aCapuchin artzAngolay18th century. 0aCapuchin artzKongo Kingdomy17th century. 0aCapuchin artzKongo Kingdomy18th century. 7aART / African.2bisacsh  aAngola.  aAtlantic World.  aCapuchins.  aChinese rites controversy.  aFranciscans.  aKongo kingdom.  aKongo.  aaccommodation.  abotanical illustrations.  acatechism.  acentral Africa.  aconversion.  across-cultural encounters.  across-cultural images.  aearly modern Atlantic.  aearly modern period.  aeighteenth century.  aindigenous ontology.  amanuscript.  amission.  anatural history.  apost-reformation.  apre-colonial Africa.  aseventeenth century.  azoological illustrations.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271094106423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter